      <lg xml:id="MTA26">
<l>eḻuvār viṭaikoḷvā rīṉṟuḻā yāṉai</l>
<l>vaḻuvā vakainiṉaintu vaikal – toḻuvār</l>
<l>viṉaiccuṭarai nantuvikkum vēṅkaṭamē vāṉōr</l>
<l>maṉaccuṭarait tūṇṭu malai</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Vēṅkaṭam that extinguishes the flame of the karma<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">The Tamil word viṉai, “action“, occurring but twelve times in the early Antāti-s, is used as a calque for Sanskrit karma throughout the bhakti period and beyond. Like karma it is in the first place neutral and has to be specified for being good (nal) or bad (aru, vem, tī, val), although if unspecified it tends to refer to bad karma. While the singular is often used to denote karma in general, the plural mostly refers to specific actions committed by an individual (cf. Po. 75.1, Pē. 76.4, 88.3).</note></l>
<l>of those who rise, who take leave, who thoughtfully worship</l> 
<l>daily<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">Here the context seems to presuppose understanding vaikal in the sense of vaikalum.</note> in a faultless manner the one with lush tulsi,</l>
<l>is the mountain that kindles the flame of the celestials’ minds.</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
